About the Updates:

Over the past decade, scientists at the Gulf of Maine Research Institute have led a body of research that highlights the rapid pace of warming in the Gulf of Maine. To help keep you informed, we share seasonal updates about conditions in the Gulf of Maine.

Note About the Data: The figures in this report are creating using remotely-sensed satellite data as part of publicly funded research efforts. Satellite sea surface temperature data used was obtained from the National Center for Environmental Information (NCEI), with all maps and figures displaying NOAAs Optimum Interpolation Sea Surface Temperature Data.

Note on Preliminary Data: This dataset has a 2-week latency period, during which values may change due to quality control measures. Any data within 14 days of the current date may be subject to change.

The Gulf of Maine

For analyses like these, it is important to be clear about the spatial extent that defines the Gulf of Maine (Figure 1), as different borders could produce different numbers. The spatial extent we use as the Gulf of Maine is displayed below. This area is consistent with previous reports and publications GMRI has produced.

For this seasonal report, we include data for Spring that follows the meteorological definitions for the seasons. Under this system the first days of March, June, September, and December each mark the start of Meteorological Spring, Summer, Fall and Winter respectively.

Spring Highlights

The average sea surface temperature (SST) for the Gulf of Maine during the spring of 2022 (March - May) was 45.34F, which is 2.9F above the long-term average of 42.35F.

These values make it the 3rd hottest spring on record for the period of 1982-2022. Read on to learn more about what SST conditions were like in the Gulf of Maine during this spring.

Looking at the data this way reveals a stunning result: SSTs in the Gulf of Maine rose above 40F in late February, 5-6 weeks sooner than they have historically.

Monthly Statistics

Looking at each month as a whole, May showed the largest difference from the long-term average, with an average temperature anomaly of 3.40F. All days this season met the criteria to be considered a marine heatwave, and each month was 2.4F or more above the 1982-2011 average.

Seasonal Trends and Anomalies in Context

The Gulf of Maine is an area of particular interest to the scientific community because of the remarkable rate of warming that it has experienced in recent years.

When looking at the average spring temperatures there is a clear long-term increase, but also a more pronounced increase that begins around 2008.

After this point both the seasonal average and the bulk of the daily temperatures remain several degrees above what we would have expected from the 30-year climatology.

This period of faster warming is part of what appears to be a distinct regime in the Gulf of Maine. The drivers of this (e.g., a weakening of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation and shifts in the path of the Gulf Stream) have been well-documented in the peer-reviewed literature, including through research by GMRI scientists.

Temperature Anomaly Record

The same trends can be seen when looking through the lens of temperature anomalies (departure from normal climate). We see the same patterns of steadily rising temperatures followed by an increase in warming in recent years.

Spring temperatures since 2008 have not fallen below 0.5C with 2012 positioned as the hottest spring at 2.22C above the 30-year summer average.

The average temperature anomaly for this spring was 1.66C / 2.99F.

Daily temperature anomalies this season peaked on 2022-05-16, at 3.14C | 5.65F degrees above the long-term average.

Ranking 2022s Temperatures

2022 is among the warmest springs seen in the Gulf of Maine during this 40+ year period. When compared against all previous springs (1982-2021), this year ranks # 3 for hottest on record.

Marine Heatwave Timeline

A marine heatwaves (MHW) is defined as a situation when SSTs exceed a threshold (usually the 90th percentile of prior daily observations) for at least 5 consecutive days. Successive heatwaves with gaps of 2 days or less are considered part of the same event. The heatwave threshold used below was 90%.

Using this broadly accepted definition, the Gulf of Maine has experienced MHW conditions for almost all of 2022. There was a very brief two-day reprieve in mid-May which was followed by a sharp climb in temperature soon-after. Because of that brevity scientists would consider the observed temperatures to be part of the same heatwave event.

The Gulf of Maine began this year experiencing MHW conditions spilling over from an event the previous year. That event began at the start of 2021 and lasted for the entirety of the year. The heatwave seen in the figure below is the tail end of that event, which persisted all the way through to June 2022.

Changing the axis to anomalies rather than temperature, the magnitude of the MHW become more clear. The most extreme anomalies of this Spring occurred at the beginning of January and in the second-half of May, with temperatures exceeding \(4\)F above the climatological average. Remember, the value of zero in this figure is the average daily temperature from the climate period of 1982-2011. Not a single day in 2022 has been \(1.5\)F of that average temperature.

Longest Heatwave on Record

The heatwave event of 2022 was actually a continuation of an historical event, the longest heatwave in the regions history.

The full heatwave event lasted a total of 535, and during that period temperatures were on average 3.87F what they were compared to the climate reference period.

Heatmap of Temperature Anomalies and Heatwave Events

Seasonal Anomaly Map

From an overhead look of the course of the Spring season, the Gulf of Maine and surrounding areas experienced above average temperatures for much of the area, but with particularly warm patches to the East of Georges Bank. The highest daily temperature anomaly of any location this period was 13.51F The highest seasonally-averaged anomaly of any location was 9.4F.

Monthly Temperature Anomalies

Average monthly temperature anomalies are displayed below. From these we can see that were concentrated just south of the Gulf of Maine in March, but by April and May the waters East of Georges Bank and near the Northeast Passage were experiencing temperatures >5C warmer than the climate of the recent past.
